MANUFACTURING PHILOSOPHY — The 787 Model
Here's the thing most people get wrong about how a stealth bomber gets built: they picture a factory floor. One building, one assembly line, wings moving down a track toward a tail section.
That's the 777 model. And it's not what's happening in Palmdale.
The B-21 follows a different logic — closer to how Boeing builds the 787 Dreamliner. Distributed subassembly. Roughly six major sections, built by Tier 1 suppliers scattered across the country, each one finishing a piece of the airframe in isolation before it ever sees another part of the plane.
(Beat.)
A wing spar takes shape in one state. A fuselage section in another. Neither supplier ever needs to see the whole aircraft — they just need to hit their interface tolerances to the micron. The plane doesn't get assembled so much as it gets converged — all six pieces arriving at Plant 42 within a production window measured in days, not weeks.
And what's visible in that final assembly count — six subassemblies — undersells what's actually happening. Because behind each of those six sections sits a depth of parts-in-process that never shows up on a headline number. Sub-suppliers feeding sub-suppliers. A supply chain with the same recursive structure the plane itself has.
(Pivot line, into the ancient thread:)
